feared to be 189 lives, it managed a direct
hit on‘ an area where work crews were just

ﬁnishing a three—year, $258 million renova-

tron.
“It’s all shot now,” said Evey, a pro-
gram manager who served as an Army

_ infantry ofﬁcer in Vietnam.

, Still, his dismay at having to start from
scratch is tempered by his conviction that

die renovations — particularly the expen-

sive structural reinforcements — helped
contain the damage and save lives.

After all, the terrorists’ weapon of
choice —- an airliner loaded with jet fuel -

. toppled the lofty towers of the World Trade
Center but left the squat Pentagon largely

intact. ,Workers were back in many ofﬁces
the next day, and two-thirds of the Pentagon

