Guns don’t mean safe ﬂights

Have you complained about having to ~

show up at the airport an hour before your
ﬂight?

Have you asked how the hijackers that
attacked New York and Washington could
get on the planes?

In the United States, airports and air-
lines themselves are responsible for security.
But they have to meet a bottom line. They
also want to keep their passengers satisﬁed —
which includes delaying them as little as
possible.

Airport security guards are often poorly
trained and poorly paid.

Following the Sept. 11 attacks, the
Federal Aviation Administration ordered
heightened security. Guards are on higher
alert, and passengers must show up two
horns before ﬂights.

But this is not enough The federal gov— _

emrnent should take over airport security
immediately. Guards must be better trained
and better paid They should also more strict-
ly enforce already existing regulations con-
cerning what a passenger can cany.

But increasing security on the ground is
not the only way to prevent future hijack-
mgs.
On Tuesday, the Air Line Pilots
Association announced that it will lobby for
legislation allowing pilots to carry guns, st11n
guns and other weapons in the cockpit. The
Justice Dept. has already placed federal air
marshals on some ﬂights.

Although the idea of air marshals and
pilots armed with guns might be comforting,
it could cause more harm than good.
Imagine a hijacker holding a person hostage,
threatening to slit her throat unless the air
marshal drops his gun. What would the air
marshal do?

What would happen if a bullet misses
its target and causes damage to the plane?

Training pilots and air marshals in areas
like martial arts and other forms of weapon-
less self—defense should be done. But they
should not carry guns. V

Another proposal is to strengthen cock-.
pit doors and lock them throughout the

ﬂight. The pilots would_ lock the doors, with _

no one else able to open them. Hijackings
would become more diﬂicult since a pilot
could just immediately land The hijacker
could not ﬂy it into a building.

Since terrorists would need a bomb
strong enough to cause other damage to the
plane to access the cockpit, this would ren-
der the hijacking pointless. ,

VV1th the more stringent security mea-
sures already in place here and in foreign air-
ports with planes leaving for the United

States,ﬂyingissaferthanintherecentpast..

People should not be overly paranoid.

Let’s justhope that those who complain
abouthavingtobeattheairportearlywill
ﬁnally realize that those few extra minutes
they have to wait could save their lives — and
those of many others.

