running at the Pit Repertory Theatre.

The two main characters, Estragon and
Vladimir, portrayed respectively by Alex
Coleman and Larry John Meyers, are sitting
in a park waiting for their “ﬁiend” Godot
Neither knows who Godot is or why they are
waiting for him. Just as the two protagonists
anxiously await his arrival, so does the audi-
enee.
The play starts with Estragon trying to
remove one of his boots. The moment
Vladimir walks on stage the two start bicker-
ing over nonsense. The topic of the argument
keepsshiﬁingandtheaudiencelaughsathow
little sense each character makes.

The two characters meet two men, Pozzo
and Lucky, during their wait. Pozzo, played
by Doug Metz, is overdramatic and egotisti-
cal. Matt Gaydos plays Pozzo’s faithﬁrl ser-
vant Lucky, who must cater to -his every need.

While the four characters interact on
stage, the audience laughs at the stupidity of
the questions each is asking to the other. None

of the characters listen, they only speak
