of the most humorous parts of the play.

Gaydos excellently fools everyone into

’ believing that he is stupid and crazy.

Following in ﬂte footsteps of “Seinfeld’s”
Kramer, he sports wild hair and eccentric
cloﬂres. His eyes are big and his mouth always
gapes. Gaydos can change his accent at any
moment and speaks quickly, but also clearly.

Pozzo and Lucky eventually leave, and
the two protagonists continue to wait for
Godot. More slapstick humor and ﬁrnny lines
follow.

The play shiﬂs when Estragon becomes
scared and Vladimir comforts him. There is
no music, only silence. Both actors do an
excellent job showing how much their ﬁ'iend-
ship means to each of them.  covers
