ering in his sleep. As the scene ends, the two
embrace.

Even though the play progresses, there is
no action, conﬂict or scene change. The few
props remain on the stage the entire time. The
story does not pick up and the plot does not
thicken Each time one of the characters
speaks, itis likeaplaywithinaplay.

“Waiting for Godot” is a very different
play in the fact thatthere is no real plot, cos-

tumes or props. The humorous lines and slap- '

stick keep the viewers watching but also ques-
tioning Beckett’s real reason for writing this
play. There is no right or wrong answer to this
dilemma The audience is left to openly inter-
pret its meaning. '

