Punks of the world rejoice: the Suicide
Machines are back, and they’ve brought a new
album.

Steal This Record is hard—hitting, straight-up
punk. It’s full of determined lyrics, trouncing gui-
tars and crashing cymbals, with a couple of sur-
prise tracks, too.

After 10 years in the music business, the
Suicide Machines show they haven’t lost their gui-
tar ferocity, gritty vocals or pounding bass-and-
drum combination.

The Suicide Machines are emphatic about
their fourth album on the Hollywood Records
label and say that it is their best album yet. By the
overall sound of the album, it’s hard to think any-
thing less.

Anthems “The Killing Blow” and ‘‘All My
People” are laced with old-school" punk inﬂu-

ences. “Unbreakable,” “Brass Ring” and “Off The
Cuff” will satisfy all thrashing needs.

“Honor Among Thieves” is an autobiographi-
cal look at the Suicide Machines and their history.

“The R.E.M. Song” covers the R.E.M. classic,
“It’s the End of the World as We Know It.” You
might think that the last band the Suicide
Machines would cover is  but they make a
convincing attempt. .

Another surprise is the combination ska/reg-
gae tune, “Stand-up.” This Bob Marley—esque
song is unexpected from the Suicide Machines,
but they- exert an impressive effort at a more
diverse sound, as well as try new techniques and
methods of expression.

With only one track breaching the four-minute
barrier, the album plays Very fast. Steal This
Record has 15 tracks, but if you walk away from
the CD player you’ll probably miss something.

Loud and raw, Steal This Record is the antithe-
sis to the “pop—punk” movement; it’s everything a
true punk fan could ever want.

Don’t do what the title implies. Steal This
Album is well worth the cash.

— Steve Mogg, staﬁ” writer

Ramblin’ men

So Many Worlds

Rambient
Immergent Records
iksktk

For once, an eclectic mix of musical genres is found on an
album other than a movie soundtrack. Porno for Pyros guitarist

Peter DiStefano and ﬁlm composer Harry Gregson—Williarns

teamed up to create the group Rambient. _

So Many Worlds, the title of Rarnbient’s first album, describes
the songs perfectly. From rap to rock, techno to piano, this album
proves that different styles can mesh and still get along.

An array of instruments and voices produces a fun and upbeat
sound. In each of the songs, bass is essential and the attitude is all
about optimism. This is where the similarities end. The electric
guitar steals the limelight in “Power” while “Killa Machine”

focuses on the smooth rapping of Divine Styler. Three songs later

» .  “Birth of a Girl” skips lyrics
altogether. Instead, piano
music and acoustic guitars
take the lead.

The cover song,
“Hunicane,” slows down the
album’s pace with the breezy
vocals of Lisbeth Scott while
simultaneously incorporating
a strong beat. This, along with
the harmonious voices in
“Fresh Skin” and the punchy
R&B rhythm of “So Many
Worlds” make up the best of
the album. Several of the

 

.. . . . .  « other songs, unfortunately,
tend to sound like techno music gone sour or the soundtrack to a
documentary on outer space. ‘

Although a good deal of the CD contains rapping, it conveys
neither the rhythm nor the power of the best hip-hop performers.
In “Burn,” the rapping resembles talking in rhymes more than it
does rapping. The beeps, synthesizers and philosophical voices
that pop out of nowhere in “All That Is” make the song so distinct
it does not easily fit into any specific category of music.

Overall, the songs are almost great to dance to, but just a lit-
tle too slow. Often, the songs lose the beat and replace it with
strange but beautiful sounds. These sounds meander along the
musical scale. They give the impression that the musicians are let-
ting the music go where it wants to.

So Many Worlds gives listeners the opportunity to hear a
diverse group of musicians as they experiment with new sounds
and blend different styles and ideas. While not very impressive,
the ﬁnal result is artistic.

— Jennifer Matson, The Pitt News

Pipe dreams

Underneath

The Verve Pipe
RCA Records
»“n£r1/2

Summer is not just a description of a
season, but also a description of music.
Summer is often associated with breezy,
mellow, beat—heavy rock, like Smash
Mouth’s “Walkin’ on the Sun” and
Sub1ime’s “Doin’ Time.” These happy sun-
shine songs sound ﬁne when they’re played
between June and August. The fact that The

Verve Pipe’s new record,
Undemeath, was released yes-
terday suggests the band must
have forgotten to change their
calendars.
Here, in the realm of sum-
mer music’s post-mortem
. slumber, Underneath is easily
under—appreciated. Its mood and atmosphere
conﬂict with the fact that temperatures are in
the 603. If you can ignore the alburn’s
eclipsed expiration date, it still has a few dia-
monds mixed in with the rough.
Underneath deﬁnes a giant departure
from the band’s RCA debut, Villains, and the
absence of gritty songwriting and electric

guitars are immediately noticeable. The soft
tracks “Only Words” and “Never Let You
Down” open the album up with reasons to
smile. Unfortunately the third installment, “I
Want All Of You,” brings the pleasantries to
a screeching halt with its lyrical bankruptcy.
Reminiscent of a nursery rhyme, lines
like, “Whisper words into your ears/I will
never bring you tears” unearth echoes of
love notes passed in third grade. Other
mediocre tracks, like “Miles Away,”
“Medicate Myself’ and “Gotta Move On”
only take tired jabs at life’s little problems.
It takes the beautifully poppy
“Happiness Is” to ﬁnally resurrect the record.
Underneath’s lone thought-provoker lies in

its ballad of a title track, the album’s last
piece, if you make it that far.

Overall, The Verve Pipe’s new effort
isn’t bad, but it’s far from great Fans of the
band’s deeper hits like “Hero” and
“Freshmen” might hear the void left by the
lack of purpose on Undemeath.

Each offering only skirns the surface of
the abstract topics of love and anger. They’re
playful, but not much else. In July,
Underneath would ﬁt right in witha humid
blend of lazy, windows—down, volume-up
cruising music.

Today it feels like holding an ice cream
cone inthe rriiddle of December.

— David J. McCarthy, The Pitt News

